Spatial Activities and Other Spatial Measures

Mikah Nelson

2023-10-10

Script Rundown

Purpose

Determine how experience in everyday activities affects spatial ability, activity experience, looking closely at video game experience. Small scale spatial tasks include the Mental Rotation Task - Shepard and Metzler (MRT), Paper Folding, and Object Assembly. We also look at Perspective Tasking tasks, such as the Spatial Orientation Task (SOT) and Road Map. Lastly we look at large scale tasks such as immersive Virtual Reality paradigms such as Dual Solutions Paradigm (DSP) using absolute pointing error and wayfinding efficiency, and a Maze task; a desktop task called Virtual SILCton measured in absolute pointing error within and between routes calculated in z-scores, and a desktop Route Learning task. Questionaires measuring everyday experience and general intelligence included here are the SoCal Spatial Activities Questionaire (SoCalSAQ), a video game experience questionnaire, and Raven’s Progressive Matrices (RPM).

Create Linear Model

Can run this script with either all NA’s or na.omit [ted], which will analyze only completely filled in rows. In this version and its corresponding results, na.omit is set to run.

Navigation Model

The navigation component of SoCalSAQ is best modeled when the predictor are large scale tasks, but is only correlated significantly with the RoadMap component in the correlation matrix. With na.omit, small scale tasks are the best fitting model, but not significantly differently than the other models.

#create linear models
#navigation and the only sig. corrr -- perspective taking
perspectNavModel <- lm(nav ~ sot+roadMap, data = standardDf)
perspectNavModelSum <- summary(perspectNavModel)
msePerspectNav <- mean(perspectNavModelSum$residuals^2)
msePerspectNav

## [1] 0.3599779
